[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Defining ArrayCarrier**\n\nI'm thinking about defining a public interface called ArrayCarrier. It has methods for names, markers, empty names, empty markers, and modes. I wonder if Java indeed requires default values for omitted elements in annotations? When I look at the annotation, it doesn't seem constrained. However, when using annotationType with getMethod, the specified method must exist. This gives me a lot to consider about how I structure the interface properly!\n\n**Inspecting annotation types**\n\nI realize that the visitor skips `java.lang.annotation` annotations at the top level when using `visitAnnotation`, but the `RecursiveAnnotationArrayVisitor` only requires the `annotationType` method. I can instantiate `AnnotationAttributes` for any annotation type name through `AnnotationMetadataReadingVisitor`. It seems like the top-level visitor bypasses the `java.lang.annotation` package but not `java.lang`. I might consider using an annotation type from the Spring library that has public array attributes. I'll need to check examples, like `org.springframework.core.annotation.AliasFor`, which has `String[]`. Let's investigate!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f21ea1f5ab8ae430169f5961fe03481a288dd766f71f0a060\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9ZY0oxDUnBzRS5pnec6xU2FqaMEk-hx95SxnxCWm8JVXPLZgmBtHN1ByLHE-Dvryp2hyryeuPng8fmw9NQ1HL3yPVwCuZXBywyM7a9z1egvZ97zZEnttekhHyCNOey1G7RoaKhn8h-nFbFT5Q4q41B-le0N3haHvWbWmAf-IKzJL6Z2W_OL0utXsHU46itpYhFm10au-Nzr7tDBoAAz4lcD_t2T2iZ1AKy_sqTozwRBngl6z4tFcsSvz345i8ehy6jF1xMbl8HFpT9Fpc7G5C3H6i0JF_qmBkA9i56n6gfa7fuga1nC2MB6NLGwGpsZAXiAsYpVl7ZiDVly5OQzsPlDYBsv9BhBeSvHSq-6iPHtzHA8_LjgxzleLfXWXU-k0XTlWVSIhpDAftE9Dlbph8x6nxJ8fZPf1Z84R1eXnP1bEm3V3cG1VFhAG9altEeJTQWwuNdynWuDibj84LFZqtZxCQCTiGile_AVJaKswUVZjK4HgFbyxnOVfIWmHJrFyKB_sccV-wZK4IRAn-qnmIoaV-Ws8WhTUmQzNJf1ye0JjatqaY3vDYsXhcVVPs0NUrtMyDhq7qxM9YSI